It was kind of you to have 520 damped out, and the result is interesting, though it does not accord with my suggestion. I do not see as yet what the crucial word in l. 4 can be.
That is, not σ̣τ̣ο̣μ̣ωτήν; cf. n. *89. As for the interpretation in l. 5, οὐ μὴν ἀλλὰ καὶ νῦν, if it can be read, is quite a good Ptolemaic phrase;
This is the reading in P.Petr. Kleon 24.5. only, the preceding ιο is puzzling. I hope to have a look at the papyrus some day soon, but fear I shall not be able to decipher any more of it.
